What is APR?APR stands for Annual Percentage Rate. It's a measure used to compare the yearly cost of borrowing money or earning interest on an investment across different products like credit cards, loans, etc. The APR includes not only the interest rate but also any additional fees or costs associated with the transaction.

For example, if you're looking at two credit card offers: one has a 15% interest rate and no annual fee, while another has a 10% interest rate but charges an $85 annual fee, the APR for the first card would be 15%, while the second might have an APR of around 19.5% (10% + $85/credit limit).

It's important to note that APR is typically higher than the nominal or simple interest rate because it includes additional costs. Therefore, when comparing financial products, it's crucial to look at their APRs rather than just their interest rates.yes

